charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got.

My sister has been courageously been fighting cancer for over a year. Having lost a Dad and a Step Dad to the awful disease I thought it was about time to give something back. Who better than the wonderful Macmillan nurses who are there when they are needed and know just what to say to quell any fears and worries.

So, to support, I have decided to do 2800 sit ups and 2800 squats through the month of February. It won’t be easy, but then fighting cancer isn’t easy and I think I have the easier option. 

I would love it if you could show your support and sponsor me, but if you can’t that’s fine, the odd word of encouragement will go a long way too. Thank you either way.

story: This year, No7 and Macmillan Cancer Support are working together to raise an incredible £1million to make a huge difference to people living with cancer. Together, we are launching a new fundraising challenge for everyone to get involved in – The Power of No7. Starting on 29th January and ending on 4th February - World Cancer Day - Team Macmillan will be taking part 7 activities from the Power of No7 bingo card, from meditation to baking, a fitness challenge and an act of kindness, there is something for everyone to get involved in. Anything you decide to donate will make a huge difference to people affected by cancer during these difficult times - we are asking for a suggested donation of £7 to help reach the £1million target. Thank you for all your support.

story:
To those of you that knew my gran, Eva Jones

Gran died peacefully on 17th January 2021

There will be limited numbers at the funeral due to government restrictions with no gathering allowed afterwards. 

It will however be broadcast live on the Internet. 

It is on 11th Feb. 

I therefore have a request for those who can't make it and those who can. 

Please could you have a drink of your favourite tipple on the eleventh, be it tea, wine or whatever. Have a drink to my gran and spend some time remembering the fun times. She was an amazing lady and she loved having fun. 

Any money you may have saved by not being able to attend or by not being able to come to a do afterwards, please consider a donation to MacMillan nurses. 

She would have liked that. 



Thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

story:
As we live/ learn to survive another lockdown (the third as I write this) some people are not only dealing with the stresses and strains of normal life but trying to cope with the fact that their vital treatment for cancer may not progress as it should.

We need to carry on the fight.

My small plan to start with is to walk/run at least 2 miles a day with my children (weather permitting) everyday and use this time to discuss people less fortunate than ourselves. If the weather is not conducive then we will do a home work out instead but still have the same discussions.

Let’s use this extra time we have to make a positive change.

story:
This year, I was to walk the Moonwalk, with a friend to raise money for cancer support. Due to the current situation, the organised walk has been cancelled. I have decided to do the walk independently in two weeks time (20km) and when I have finished my daughter will video herself cutting my hair to donate to Little Princess Trust, who make wigs for children with cancer.

I have cut my hair for cancer previously, in 2016. I was galvanised by a legendary fund raiser to do so and last year he lost his own battle with cancer. Today I found a Birmingham City baby cup he and his wife gave us 17 years ago for our son- to me as a Villa Fan and my husband as an Arsenal fan, with a glint in their eyes (it has not been used lol) That was a sign...do it...so I will.

I really hope you can help to reach my target, so Macmillan can carry on their tremendous work, one so close to many of our hearts. Thank you- Sarah

story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. 

2020 was a tough year wasn't it. 

Imagine how much tougher it gets when you are diagnosed with cancer. That's exactly what happened to my brother-in-law. And yet, he has bourn it with such calm, such determination to beat it. It's humbling, and I sat there thinking, "what can I do?"

Well. I have a bike. So I created a 1,000 mile long, 14 stage "Tour of England". A sustained challenge where I have to keep going. Despite the saddle sore, the aching knees, the gripping tiredness.

So, if I put in the sweaty miles...can you chip in some pounds?

Macmillan give people with cancer everything they’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are their worries. They’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help they can’t support everyone who needs them.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

Many thanks

Richard

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
my Husband was diagnosed with Lung Cancer (Adenocarcinoma) last year. Adenocarcinoma is a cancer that begins in the Glandular Cells. it is an incurable Cancer. tommy is receiving treatment called immunotherapy. 

Immunotherapy is a type of Cancer treatment that helps your immune system fight Cancer. The treatment leaves him tired and sore. 

My husband Tommy is only 35 years old, we have 2 boys John (15) and Thomas (11) the hardest thing in the world is telling your children that there Dad has an incurable Cancer. tommy gets breathless and tired very easily he cant walk a far distance or do any of the fun things he used to do like play football or go snowboarding he cant even have a game of football with his boys. to be honest we are living a nightmare.

The Macmillan Cancer nurses have been amazing Tommy's Cancer nurse is called Molly. she is very patient and as you can imagine we have loads of questions but nothing is a bother to her. she answers all the questions in a way we can understand. She is always on the other end of the phone. nothing is too much trouble for the Macmillan Nurses.

story:
Nige, Luke, Craig, Vanessa & Jo have decided to get motivated for a fabulous cause this February.  We are working as a team to hit the total target of 631km/392miles by either walking or running over the 28 day period.  

We agreed this challenge will not only help us feel united during difficult times but provide a focus, help with mental wellbeing and also our physical health.  

No doubt there will be some competitiveness along the way!

The work that Macmillan does speaks for itself and sadly too many of us have been impacted in some way by the horrible "C" word!  The aim of our challenge is to raise vital funds for such a worthy charity during such difficult times where scheduled events have had to be cancelled.

For those that wish to support us, we thank you.

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.

This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. 

St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve.  

During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country.

"I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." 
Tom Willis, volunteer 

Will you support me and help make a difference?

story:
This is the JustGiving page, set up in memory of David Pope, to raise money for the British Heart Foundation. 

Rather than sending flowers to the funeral we thought it would be a good opportunity to raise much needed funds for the Salvation Army and the British Heart Foundation.

Both of these charities were close to David’s heart and he would have appreciated the chance to do something positive during this desperately sad time.   We thank you for any contribution you are able to give however large or small, rest assured any donation made is passed directly to the charities.  

Thank you very much for your support.
David’s Family

eventName: In memory of Professor Kenneth  Barker CBE
story:
Kier Group has selected the British Heart Foundation, the biggest independent funder of cardiovascular research in the UK, as its new corporate charity partner. The two-year partnership will help in the charitys aim of increasing awareness of cardiovascular disease, raise £250,000 for vital research in to heart and circulatory conditions as well as train 1,500 Kier colleagues in the lifesaving first aid, CPR.

The British Heart Foundation is funding life saving research to help end heartbreak for the seven million people in the UK living with cardiovascular disease. For over 50 years it has pioneered research that has transformed the lives of people living with heart and circulatory conditions and has been pivotal to offering vital treatments that are changing the fight against heart disease.

eventName: Walk, Run or Cycle for Sarah
story: Thanks for visiting our team fundraising page. We work for Which? and we are fundraising for the British Heart Foundation in memory of our friend and colleague Sarah Price, who passed away suddenly last year at the age of 39. Sarah was a wonderful person; she excelled in her job but was also a committed team-player, going to great lengths to help her team members day-in, day-out. She was a brilliant friend: funny and kind, someone who always made time for everyone she encountered. We continue to miss her greatly. Sarah was a big fan of Welsh rugby and so we are planning to run, walk or cycle a combined distance that will stretch from our Bristol office, where Sarah worked, to the Principality Stadium in Cardiff and back again, which is around 86 miles in total. We plan to do this over the weekend of 27 - 28 February 2021, being the weekend closest to both St. David's Day and Sarah's 5-year anniversary since she started at Which?. Each participant will undertake 5km, either walking, running or cycling, to help us get to the total distance. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to donations that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

February is National Heart Month, and the NKD Kind team encourage you to raise your heart rate a little more this month.

On Wednesday 24th February, we are replacing our monthly Tea & Talk, with Talk & Walk to raise money for the British Heart Foundation and in memory of our dear Nab.

Let’s use an hour blocked out on this day to take a walk, or even a jog if you feel like it. Take pictures of what you find on your journey and post them in the CC Cafe.

We also encourage you to send a £5 donation to raise money for British Heart Foundation to our JustGiving page

story:
On the 22nd February it's a very special birthday, Gordon Macdonald is turning 90! He had hoped to repeat the event held on his 80th, an evening of music and dance with friends and family, however the current pandemic has spoilt these plans.

A message from Gordon...

Margaret had a successful major heart operation (so successful that she was back in the sea on Nefyn beach last year) and I'm waiting for a heart operation at the moment. 

Anyone who wishes to acknowledge this milestone birthday, please kindly donate to the British Heart Foundation, as I would be so grateful for your support.

I hope to have a proper event to celebrate in the near future!

Many thanks,

Mac

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting Wickham Courts Page. We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation and we are so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can. Many thanks from all at Wickham Court School!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Anyone who knows me, knows how hard this will be! 

I am doing a dechox for the month of March which is giving up sweets and chocolate. I don’t think I have ever gone a day over the past few years without my chocolate fix! This is going to be a challenge but so worth it. 

The money raised will go to the British heart foundation for much needed research. 

Please give anything that you can I would really appreciate it. Xx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
In November 2020, we sadly lost our beautiful Mam Gu, Christine Homfray. She was the most wonderful lady and matriarch of the family. 

Our beautiful Mam Gu was happy, healthy and fit as a fiddle but passed suddenly of an Aortic rupture which has left us all heartbroken.

I eat chocolate every single day, it’s my weakness! So this March I’m giving it all up in memory of Mam Gu and to raise awareness that no matter how fit and healthy you appear to be, your heart is always at risk. 

Please help me to raise money for the British Heart Foundation.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

Not only is this to support a great charity but my dad lost a great cycle friend to a heart attack and although I didn't no him personally I feel passionate that I should should support a charity In his name and complete a marathon walk not only in memory of him, but for my own personal challenge to myself, life is hard and I've battled my own personal problems through out my early teens and into my late twenties and I want to do something positive for myself, I only started walking recently and find it a very positive thing mentally and physically and would appreciate your support through this page, life has been tough for all of us lately, by doing this challenge we can remember the  past and look to the future in a positive light, and on the way help a great  charity too.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. eventName: RAF Benson to Op RESCRIPT challenge
story:
A team of us from the Survival Equipment Section at RAF Benson will be completing a challenge of traveling the distance of 1,082 miles throughout February. It will be completed by running, walking, cycling, and rowing.


This distance is equivalent to a return journey from RAF Benson where we are based, to Kinloss Barracks in Scotland. With urgent response within 48 hours we deployed there on Op RESCRIPT for just over three months. This was to support the Scottish Ambulance Service as part of Military Aid to Civilian Authorities in the battle against COVID-19.


We are raising money for Guidedogs UK charity for this challenge.


Every hour In the UK someone loses their sight.This affects all ages from young children to the elderly. Helping to support this charity can make a big difference to their lives. It costs on average £63,000 for one guide dog from birth to retirement.


Have a look at the link below to see how your donations are spent.


https://www.guidedogs.org.uk/about-us/how-your-money-is-helping/

charity.description: We fundraise to enhance Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people. Donations help to fund advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, pioneering research and rebuilding and refurbishment.
charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story: Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at GOSH. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support and everyone in Team GOSH taking on the iconic 2021 London Marathon will be helping to give seriously ill children the chance of a better future. For more information about the work GOSH does and to find out where Team GOSH's fundraising will go visit the website: https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Wednesday 27th January 2021 started as a normal day.  By the end of the day Lleyton a pupil at my school, had been blue lighted to Great Ormond Street and successfully operated on for a bleed to the brain. I cannot fully express how amazing the team at Great Ormond Street are, and as a member of a community school I want to push myself to do something out of my comfort zone, to raise money for this amazing hospital. If you would like to contribute in any way, we would be really grateful.

For further information please contact me at cjones@maplegrove.herts.sch.uk

story:
Neil, Max and Patrick wanted to take on a big challenge in 2021 after getting a bit fitter during lockdown but also wanting to raise money for a charity and give back.
After hearing from a few fellow Global-e employees who were working for a charity called Radio Lollipop at Great Ormond Street, we thought combining a 350 mile cycle with a charity close to peoples hearts at the company - we were in! 
We then brought a family member (Freddie) and close friend (Archie) in to complete the team of 5 that is going take on this challenge next year and raise £8,000 for GOSH!

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Hi everyone, thanks for taking the time to visit my fundraising page!

The charity I have chosen to run my 10k for is the Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity.  

Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). As many as five children a day lose their lives to a rare disease, yet only 5% of UK research funding is spent on projects relating to child health. 

My aim is to raise a minimum of £100 which can help fund medical equipment, child and family support services and research, in order to support children to continue a safe and happy life.

 So, I have decided to start my 2021 with a challenge and keep supporting children and doing my part to help save lives at the same time. Every child needs a hero!

Any donations would be appreciated, thank you for your support!

charity.name: Marie Curie
owner: Ruthin and Denbigh Marie Curie Fundraising Group
story:
Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peoples homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.

During this Covid time there is  even more demand than usual on the services offered by Marie Curie, in homes & hospices.  We know that you would all normally buy a Marie Curie daffodil at this time of year during the annual Great Daffodil appeal - please be generous and support on line to help Marie Curie help others

Please feel free to change the amount on the DONATE page to whatever you feel comfortable giving - the minimum amount is £2.

Just Giving does charge for running this fundraising service but we have checked with Marie Curie and been reassured that this is a far more cost effective way to raise money that handling donations 'in-house'

eventName: Ride 180 Miles in one week - to help fund crucial Marie Curie nursing
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am trying to raise money for Marie Curie who provide essential care when a patient and family most need it.

My company have partnered with Marie Curie for several years now and I have had the pleasure of riding London to Paris raising funds for them.

We now have 'Challenge 180' which is linked with how much it costs to provide one night of critical care @ £180.

My challenge is to ride 180 miles or more in one week during February on my indoor bike. It seems such a small effort compared to the effort it takes for a charity such as Marie Curie to provide the care they do, but it's my way of saying well done and thank you so much.

My target is £180 to help cover one critical night of care for someone who needs it. I would really appreciate any donations to help me meet my target.

I will add updates each day of the week in question to let you know how my highs and lows of hour sin the saddle are going.

Thank you for reading my JustGiving page.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Tony (Gramps) passed away at home at the age of 92 on Wednesday 20th January 2021, shortly after moving to Ashby after his wife, Dora died in July 2020. Tony had bladder cancer for many years which recently metastacised.

His daughter, Sue died of cancer 20 years ago and ever since Tony had been a dedicated volunteer and supporter of Marie Curie. To remember him we've set up this page so that those suffering at the hands of cancer and their families may receive support and care. 

If you can spare anything, please consider donating in her memory.

story: This May marks ten years since we lost my best friend's sister and Marie Curie were instrumental in giving her the best quality of life in her final months as she battled with aggressive stomach and brain cancer. Without them, her family wouldn't have been able to cope during such a difficult time and the support they offered was unbelievable.  Please give absolutely anything you can to help raise as much as possible. Thank you for your support.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page

At the end of last year one of my best pals Tam Thomson got diagnosed with Lung Cancer (Adenocarcinoma) Adenocarcinoma is a Cancer that begins in the Glandular cells Which is an incurable Cancer.


Many of my family have battled cancer also,  so I want to support this great charity.


I am going to be running 50 miles in February to help support Tommy & Michelle. ( 50 miles might not seem like a lot, but I deteste running 🤣)

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Teignmouth Lifeboat Station is located in the working harbour of Teignmouth on the River Teign, the station’s Atlantic 85 class inshore lifeboat being kept in the original 1862 boathouse. Teignmouth lifeboat volunteers carry out around 40 rescues every year.

Teignmouth Fundraising Team fundraise across the Teign Valley, Newton Abbott, Totnes, Dawlish and surrounding areas with the volunteer fundraisers helping to provide the funding to support for the lifesaving work of Teignmouth’s volunteer lifeboat crew who are available 24/7 for anyone who needs their help.

We rely on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea - your donation to this page will help support the running costs of stations in the South West including our lifeboat based in Teignmouth and its volunteer crew.
title: Teignmouth RNLI Lifesavers Fund
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
Name: Teignmouth RNLI Lifesavers Fund

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
RNLI lifeboats in Scotland protect hundreds of communities with a 24-hour search and rescue service. Our volunteer crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. It costs an average of £155k to run a lifeboat station in Scotland but with the implications of Covid-19, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to help keep our lifeboats afloat. Can you help?

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
owner: Inverness and North Kessock RNLI fundraising
story:
RNLI lifeboats in Scotland protect hundreds of communities with a 24-hour search and rescue service. Our volunteer crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. It costs an average of £155k to run a lifeboat station in Scotland but with the implications of Covid-19, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to help keep our lifeboats afloat. Can you help?

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

Hi there! Thank you for visiting my page, my name is Alexandra, I am 23 and I have decided to take part in the Big Winter Wander to give back to a charity I have supported for many years and, of course, to raise funds that will go towards the amazing efforts of WWF. Your donations will be used in the ambitious programmes WWF are currently working on, such as restoring nature/habitats, establishing “green corridors”, making our food system sustainable, tackling climate change and much more. If you would like any more info on this please visit their website! 

I have always been extremely passionate about the environment and wildlife and try to keep up to date with current affairs concerning the planet, therefore this cause means a great deal to me personally. Over Feb 2021 I will attempting to walk 10k on each of my walks (just as a personal goal for myself) visiting some hopefully new places and enjoying nature whilst obviously respecting the guidelines put in place over lockdown. 

Any donations big or small are greatly appreciated!

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

story:
Helllo!

So me and some of my milk friends are getting together to partake in a walking challenge! This involves us walking 100km (roughly 62 miles) in under 30 hrs. We will be walking throughout the night to ensure we complete the challenge.

Trailwalker UK supports the incredible work of both Oxfam Great Britain and The Gurkha Welfare Trust.


The Gurkhas are soldiers from Nepal who are recruited into the British Army and have been for over 200 years. They are renowned for their loyalty, professionalism and bravery. We ensure that Gurkha veterans, their widows and their wider communities are able to live with dignity in their home-country of Nepal.

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
From the 8th-21st February 2021, Friends of Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders) around the country will come together for a STRAVATHON in an effort to raise funds for MSF’s LIFE SAVING WORK.

Participants from around the world will run, cycle, walk or take part in any sport they fancy and record their activity in the Strava Club.

Since its creation in 1971, MSF has been at the forefront of humanitarian medical aid. Its mission to provide lifesaving medical care to those most in need has had – and continues to have – a meaningful impact globally.

Your donation matters. It is thanks to people like you that MSF can carry through its life saving work in over 60 countries. These are a few of the many ways your donation can help others:

  • £3 buys 312 ibuprofen tablets to provide pain relief.
  • £10 provides vaccination against measles for 21 children.
  • £15 buys enough ready-to-use therapeutic food (RUTF) to treat 2 severely malnourished children.
  • £20 affords Hepatitis B vaccination for 62 people.
  • £30 provides clean linen and gowns for 2 surgical operations and help prevent the spread of infection.
  • £45 could cover the cost of putting a doctor in a crisis field for a day.
  • £65 buys a foldable stretcher to quickly and safely remove an injured person from danger.
  • £73 could treat up to 130 people with malaria.
  • £95 provides a year’s supply of anti-retroviral drugs for 1 person.
  • £97 could pay for crutches for 4 patients with leg injuries.
  • £188 buys a basic surgical kit to enable an MSF surgeon to carry out surgery in a crisis zone. 

These are just some of the ways you are helping MSF make a difference. Every little bit helps, so please consider supporting us today – and it is all for a great cause!

More than 95% of the funds that MSF have to work with come from private individuals like yourself, which allows MSF to have a unique commitment towards neutrality, impartiality and independence.

If you are interested in taking part, please note registrations close on the 7th February 2021. Register your details here: https://forms.gle/hVZoyuVdrLpLpKJq9

Find out more at the Facebook event: *link*

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
When doing some research about water, Elijah discovered that the average distance children and women walk to collect water is 6km, and he was inspired to do something to help. For many, the daily routine to get water takes over their lives. Children often miss out on the chance to go to school.

Elijah, Cónán and Frankie (all 11 years old) are raising money for WaterAid, to help bring clean water and toilets to vulnerable communities around the world. On Sunday 31st January, they are going to walk an approximately 6km round-trip collect water in buckets and carry it to their homes, in different parts of Walthamstow.

The total amount raised will be matched by the UK government (until the 4th Feb) so your donation will go even further!
title: Walthamstow kids for clean water
pageSummary: We are raising money for clean water and toilets because a 6km trip to get water means no time for school

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
We recently heard how girls of our age walk miles to collect dirty water because they do not have access to a tap in their community.  We want to do something to help!

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

5th Sketty Guides have decided to collate 150 photographs of water before 13th February.  Our collage will represent the 150 litres of water each one of us uses each day in the UK.  

Please sponsor us today and help us change lives for the better.

charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
I too had to walk everyday, sometimes twice a day to fetch water for everyday use and needs. It was not a welcomed chore. Nevertheless, in some countries people have no choice but to walk miles to fetch water for themselves and their families. And this is why I’ve decided to walk 4km every day for the month of March so that one day women and children won't have to walk miles carrying a bucket of water on their heads. I’m walking to raise money so that people living in remote villages where water is scarce can have access to clean and safe running water in their villages..


Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
